commitResults.messageBody:
Let's call the chatbot "Nick".

Let's implement an initial skeletal version of the ip that simply greets the user and exits.

Included *.class in the .gitignore file which will not be committed as
it should not be revision controlled.

Let's,

* Add a file containing ASCII content of name to the root of the
  project directory for uniqueness and customization.

* Improve skeletal version of Duke so that it echos commands entered by the user, and exits when the user types the command bye.

Let's,
* Create a fixed size array ( String[100] ) to store the items.
* Store whatever text entered by the user and display them back to the user when requested.

Let's,

* Add the ability to mark tasks as done.
* Add the ability to change the status back to not done.
* Implement extension (A-Classes) with Task class to represent tasks.

Tweak the code to comply with a given coding standard.
Link: https://se-education.org/guides/conventions/java/basic.html

commitResults.messageTitle: Nick.java: Change class name from Duke to Nick
commitResults.messageBody: Change class name from Duke to Nick for better customization.

Let's implement,
* ToDos: tasks without any date/time attached to it e.g., visit new theme park.
* Deadlines: tasks that need to be done before a specific date/time e.g., submit report by 11/10/2019 5pm.
* Events: tasks that start at a specific date/time and ends at a specific date/time e.g., (a) team project meeting 2/10/2019 2-4pm (b) orientation week 4/10/2019 to 11/10/2019
* A-Inheritance: use classes Todo, Deadline and Event classes to inherit from a Task class.

Use the input/output redirection technique to semi-automate the testing of Duke.

Let's,
* Duplicate the name.txt file to the text-ui-test folder.
* Modify the while loop in Nick.java from while(true) to
  while(input.hasNextLine()).
* Add the input instructions to the input.txt file and expected results
  to the EXPECTED.TXT file in text-ui-test folder.
Critically examines the code and refactor to improve the code quality where necessary.

Let's,
* Abstract printByeMsg(), printAddTaskMsg(), printIntroName(),
  printIntroMsg() to the UserInterface class.

commitResults.messageBody:
Let's,

* Teach chatbot to deal with errors such as incorrect inputs entered by
  the user.

* Handle invalid commands by throwing NickException() object and
  handling StringIndexOutOfBoundsException

* Create a new NickException class

Let's,
* Create a command package containing our Deadline, Event, Task and Todo
  classes.

Let's,
* Use the Java Collections class ArrayList<Task> to store our tasks.

Let's,

* Create Ui class to deal with interactions with the user.

* Create Storage class to deal with loading tasks from the file and
  saving tasks in the file.

* Create Parser class to deal with making sense of the user command.

* Create TaskList class to contain the task list eg: it has operations
  to add/delete tasks in the list.

* Implement stretch goal to extract *Command classes which inherit from
  an abstract Command class and store them in command package.

Let's,

* Package ui, storage and parser class

Let's,

* Store deadline dates as a java.time.LocalDate (or java.time.LocalDateTime) in your task objects.
* Accept dates in a format such as yyyy-mm-dd format (e.g., 2019-10-15) and print in a different format such as MMM dd yyyy e.g., (Oct 15 2019).
